Studying SNAP retailers during the Great Recession

Jerry Shannon

June 29, 2018

This paper provides a research rationale and methodology for a dataset of SNAP retailers from 2008-2017, available through this Github repository.

Background

Research on geographic access to healthy food outlets dates to the early 2000s. A group of British researchers first used the term food desert to describe neighborhoods without access to healthy and affordable food, basing it on an interview with neighborhood residents (Cummins and Macintyre 1999; Wrigley 2002). This term and its emphasis on the influence of neighborhood food environments quickly gained traction. A 2017 review, for instance, identified 432 articles measuring food environments (Lytle and Sokol 2017). Of those, 65% used geographic analysismaking use of geographic information systems (GIS) to measure proximity to varying store types such as supermarkets and convenience stores. In the United States, the 2008 Farm Bill mandated a national analysis of food accessibility (Walker, Keane, and Burke 2010). The Food Access Research Atlas is one result of this mandate, providing a widely used map of what it terms low income, low access census tracts where supermarkets are distant (USDA Economic Research Service 2014). The federal Healthy Food Financing Initiative is an example of policies developed based on these maps to improve food access. This program targets food deserts specifically, providing both public and private money for new stores or redevelopment of existing sites (Office of Community Services 2011).

Despite the popularity of food deserts as a metaphor, both the term and the geographic methodology have been criticized in recent years. While desert conjures up the image of places where food is simply unavailable, neighborhoods identified as food deserts often have abundant sources of largely processed, nutrient poor foods: fast food and corner stores, for example. As an alternative, some have suggested that the term food swamp more accurately describes these areas (Cooksey-Stowers, Schwartz, and Brownell 2017; Fielding and Simon 2011). While geographic analysis has identified multiple neighborhoods with poor access to supermarkets, policies that spur the creation of new stores have shown little if no impact on the dietary quality of nearby residents (Ghosh-Dastidar et al. 2017). Most geographic analyses also focus on the potential role of the residential food environment, and only recently has research begun to incorporate the mobility of individuals and the ways they navigate the food options available to them throughout the day (Widener and Shannon 2014; Chrisinger et al. 2018; Li and Kim 2017). This work highlights the ways that low-income households do access food sources outside their residential neighborhoods, especially for lower prices or better perceived food quality (Shannon 2016). At the same time, this mobility may also often entail high time or economic costs and rely on extended social networks.

In addition to these critiques, ecological metaphors for food accessibilitywhether deserts or swampsdeserve scrutiny. These terms implicitly rely on a free market model, describing neighborhood food environments as natural features that emerge as part of open economic activity. They also focus attention on low-access neighborhoods as aberrations in an otherwise healthy and habitable landscape, areas that just need remediation (Shannon 2014). Yet a parallel line of research on food justice suggests that food deserts are by no means natural (Alkon and Agyeman 2011). Rather, they are part of larger racialized inequalities inherent to both urban development and industrialized food production (McClintock 2011). In this sense, terms like supermarket redlining (Eisenhauer 2001; Zhang and Ghosh 2016) or food apartheid (Brones 2018) may better describe the processes at play. Indeed, real estate redlining was a driving force for suburbanization for much of the 20th century (Jackson 1987) and supermarkets as a model emerged alongside these booming suburban communities. Studying the distribution of food retailers, therefore, reveals the ways that their location has been shaped by policies across geographic scales. It questions language that frames food environments as shaped primarily by the workings of the free market, focusing instead on the ways racial and economic inequality are implicitly and explicitly hardwired into the food system. In doing so, this approach highlights the need for systemic change rather than locally targeted policies.

The Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP, formerly known as food stamps) is one key systemic policy mechanism that shapes local food environments. The food stamp program originated in the Great Depression. Originally a direct commodity surplus distribution program designed to support struggling farmers, the program was revised to include the growing supermarket industry, providing vouchers redeemable for food purchases (Moran 2011). Revived during the Kennedy administration in the 1960s, the food stamp program has proven to be one of the most durable income support programs over the last fifty years, outlasting other programs such as Aid for Families with Dependent Children (AFDC) that were heavily curtailed during welfare reform in the 1990s (Gritter and MacRobert 2015). Supporters point to both its economic stimulus and effectiveness at lowering rates of food insecurity among vulnerable populations (Bartfeld et al. 2015).

In 2017, SNAP provided $63.6 billion dollars of financial assistance to over 42 million individuals nationwide (U.S. Dept. of Agriculture 2018). SNAP benefitscurrently delivered electronically and redeemable through a electronic card similar to credit cardscan be redeemed at authorized retailers for a wide range of food items. In contrast to direct relief for working families, such as commodity surplus distribution, SNAP works in coordination with private markets, providing benefits to producers, distributors, and retailers in addition to low-income households (Hanson 2010). The spatial effect of SNAPs economic stimulus has rarely been analyzed. In times of economic hardship, such as the Great Recession of 2008, SNAP may provide counter-cyclical economic support not just for low-income households, but also for retailers. This period thus offers the chance to understand how SNAP may shape local food environmentsproviding economic support for certain types of food retailers. In this sense, SNAP as a policy actively shapes the landscape of foods available to consumers.

As noted above, recent research on food access has focused on the mobility of individuals, asking how and where individuals interact with the food system (Shannon 2016, Widener and Shannon (2014)). This research provides valuable insight on how access to transit, cultural preferences, store perceptions, and reliance on social networks matter to everyday food provisioning patterns. Focusing on the shifting landscape of SNAP retailers provides a parallel line of research, one that focuses on the mobility of food retailers, their responses to shifting policy environments andto shifting demographic and development patterns. This mobility reveals the patterns of capital investment by food retailers, underscoring how some neighborhoods may be effectively redlined based on racial or economic characteristics. Because it works through market based mechanisms, SNAP interacts with these processes, providing signifciant economic incentive for retailers, even if the effects of this incentive may be uneven. For example, previous research in Georgia has found that higher SNAP enrollment fueled significant growth among small retailers in the years after the recession, but had little effect for large retailers (Shannon et al. 2018).

This longitudinal, national dataset contains data on the location of SNAP retailers each June from 2008 through 2017. Through analyses of these data, future research can better articulate how increased participation in SNAP impacted the geography of SNAP retailers. While most large stores participate in SNAP, participation is less consistent for small retailers. Our previous research indicated that roughly half the stores entering SNAP during this time frame were present prior to the recession (Shannon et al. 2018). As a result, these data provide the best insight into how some retailers relied on the financial stimulus provided during this period and the potentially disparate effects of this shifting landscape on the food sources available to SNAP clients. It reveals how SNAP may have ameliorated or enhanced existing retailer redlining in communities across the country. Lastly, it provides a resource for more in depth local research on food quality and selection within stores or interactions between retailers and local residents.

Methods and data characteristics

These store data were obtained through direct email contact with the USDA Benefit Redemption Division. In response to a records request, the agency sent a CD with retailer listings on June 30 for the years 2008 through 2017. These were provided as separate Excel files. To combine them, I used this R script. This file reads in each Excel file, adds a year column, and then combines them into a single listing. Entries with identical names and addresses are identified by shifting the year column from long to wide format. I then added a unique store ID for each line, as USDA does not provide their identifier when releasing public data.

Some retailers may have their names or addresses shift slightly from year to yearB & H Foods, for example, could become B&H foods. Fuzzy record matching is typically used to address this issue, but for a dataset with over 400,000 records, this is computationally challenging. Zane Page, a student in computer science at UGA, created a Python script to efficiently complete this comparison (link to code), and the most likely matches were reviewed manually. In the end, only 19 records were combined through fuzzy matching. The resulting dataset lists 425,869 retailers.

USDA also only provides locational data (latitude and longitude) for current retailers (n=261,500). For the additional locations, I used a three step process to add coordinates. First, retailers without coordinates were geocoded using ESRIs world geocoding service. Of these results, I selected addresses with relatively poor accuracy for further geocoding, those with match types of postal codes, postal locations, extended street address, and street name only. These were geocoded with the Google Maps API using the ggmap package in R. I used any addresses provided by Google that had greater accuracy than those provided by ESRI. Lastly, all points were visually inspected and severalparticularly in the Virgin Islandswere manually geocoded using Bing Maps. The data contains columns for the methods of geocoding (ESRI, Google, Manual, or USDA) and the match type were applicable. See the documentation for ESRI and Google linked above for more information about the match types.

In addition to these locational data, I have also provided a separate file with FIPS codes and other identifiers specific to each data point, the state, county, and tract FIPS codes and the metropolitan statistical area (if applicable). I have also included a tract FIPS codegisjn_tctthat is compatible with data from the National Historical GIS database at the University of Minnesota. These can be joined to the main store listing through the store identifier (storeid).

USDA provides 17 types of retail classification based on store characteristics. While this granularity can be useful, I have also created a set of six store classifications that can simplify analysis. The crosswalk for these store types is shown below.

Data summary

The figure below shows the count of each retailer group over the study period. Small retailers are by far the largest of these categories (95,311 stores in 2008), followed by supermarkets (34,072) and grocers (27,374). While all store types see a significant increase in the first part of the study period, they follow divergent paths after 2011. Grocers, specialty retailers, and other stores (commissaries and delivery services) decline sharply at that point, while small retailers, supermarkets, and local foods stores continue to grow at a modest pace. While the overall trend for small retailers is similar to that of local foods and supermarkets, the magnitude of the change varies. Small retailers increased by 87% or 83,378 stores during the time period. Local foods sites increased at a much greater rate (584%) but this also represents a relatively modest raw count of 6,502 new retailers nationwide. Supermarkets added only 3,494 new locations during this time, a 10% increase.

store_counts<-stores %>%
  gather(Y2008:Y2017,key="year",value="count") %>%
  filter(count==1) %>%
  group_by(year,store_group) %>%
  summarise(count=n()) %>%
  mutate(year_n=substr(year,2,5)) %>%
  select(-year) %>%
  rename("Year"=year_n)

ggplot(store_counts,aes(x=Year, y=count, group=store_group)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line()+
  facet_wrap(~store_group,scales="free_y")+
  theme_minimal()+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60, hjust = 1),
        axis.title=element_blank())

Count of retailers by year and store type

The figure below shows the normalized count of retailers by state/territory, which illustrates the consistency of these trends. The red line on these graphs represents a z score of 0, or the mean count across the time period in each area. Local foods and small retailers are both tightly clustered, following trends similar to those seen in the previous figure. Among small retailers, the only notable decrease is in the Virgin Islands, though both Guam and Washington, D.C. also saw drops in 2016 and 2017.

Among other store types, the trends are more diverse. Specialty retailers generally follow a downward trend in later years, similar to that seen the previous figure. However, some states including Colorado, Nevada, and Arizona saw notable increases toward the end of the study period. Supermarkets show a general upward trend in many states, but Nevada, Ohio, and Michigan are among the states where the number of supermarkets decreased across the time period. Lastly, among grocers, the trends vary widely across areas.

store_counts_z<-stores %>%
  gather(Y2008:Y2017,key="year",value="count") %>%
  filter(count==1) %>%
  group_by(state,year,store_group) %>%
  filter(store_group %in% c("Supermarket","Grocer","Small retail","Specialty","Local foods")) %>%
  summarise(count=n()) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(state,store_group) %>%
  mutate(count_mean=mean(count),
         count_sd=sd(count),
    count_z=((count-count_mean)/count_sd))
 

ggplot(store_counts_z,aes(x=year, y=count_z,group=state)) +
  geom_line(colour="#6a6c70") +
  geom_hline(colour="red",aes(yintercept=0))+
  facet_wrap(~store_group)+
  theme_minimal()+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60, hjust = 1),
        axis.text.y = element_blank(),
        axis.title = element_blank())

Yearly normalized count of retailers by state and store type

The geographic data in this dataset make mapping the distribution of data a simple task using most GIS capable software (e.g., QGIS, R, ArcMap). The data contain fields for metropolitan statistical areas, and so stores can be easily subsetted by state, county, or urban region. For example, here are maps of each major store type in Chicago in 2008.

stores_chi<-stores %>%
  filter(msa_fips==16980) %>%
  select(-Y2009:-Y2017) %>%
  gather(Y2008,key="year",value="present") %>%
  filter(present==1)

stores_chi_sf<-st_as_sf(stores_chi,coords=c("X","Y"),crs=4326)

tm_shape(layers_all) +
  tm_polygons(col="white",border.col="#bfc0c1",lwd=0.7)+
tm_shape(stores_chi_sf)+
  tm_dots(col="black",size=0.2) +
tm_facets(by="store_group",
          free.coords=FALSE) +
tm_layout(legend.title.size=3,
  legend.text.size =2,
  legend.bg.alpha = 1,
  panel.label.size = 2)

SNAP authorized retailers in Chicago, 2008

Using a basic Euclidean distance measure, I calculated the distance to the third closest authorized retailer in Chicago in 2008 and 2010. I measured the distance from each block centroid and then created a population weighted mean at the tract levelsee this script for distance calculation. The map below shows the change between those years. Areas in red or orange are those where distance to the third closest retailer increased during this time. Areas in green are those where distance to the third closest retailer decreased. I use the third closest retailer for this map because it provides a better measure of store density in an area and is less sensitive to the effects of a single store location.

layers_all_df<-layers_all

The significant increases in SNAP retailers affected the overall makeup of retailers available within cities. While the number of supermarkets increased overall during this time period, they decreased as a percentage of all SNAP retailers during this time, primarily due to booming numbers of small retailers. The figure below shows supermarkets as a share of total retailers among the ten largest metro areas. Supermarkets as a share of retailers declined in each city. In Atlanta, they fell from 27% to 15% of all retailers, while in Detroit the decrease was from 14% to 10%.

msa_count<-stores %>%
  filter(msa_fips>0) %>%
  group_by(msa_name) %>%
  summarise(count=n()) %>%
  top_n(10,count)

stores_msa_chg<-stores %>%
  filter(msa_name %in% msa_count$msa_name) %>%
  gather(Y2008:Y2017,key="year",value="present") %>%
  filter(present==1) %>%
  group_by(msa_name,msa_short,store_group,year) %>%
  summarise(store_count=n()) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(msa_name,msa_short,year)%>%
  mutate(store_count_all=sum(store_count),
         store_pct=round(store_count/store_count_all*100,2)) %>%
  filter(year %in% c("Y2008","Y2017") & 
         max(store_count_all)>250)

dot_plot<-function(st_group){
  stores_msa_select<-stores_msa_chg %>% filter(store_group==st_group)
  
  ggplot(stores_msa_select,aes(x=year,y=store_pct,group=msa_name,label=msa_short)) +
  geom_line(color="#045ff2")+
  geom_point(color="#045ff2")+
  geom_text_repel(
    data = subset(stores_msa_select,year=="Y2017"),
    nudge_x     = 0.5,
    size  =  4,
    direction    = "y",
    hjust = -0.5)+
  theme_minimal()+
  labs(y="% of all retailers",x="Year")+
  facet_wrap(~store_group,scales="free_y")
}

dot_plot("Supermarket")

Supermarkets as a percentage of all SNAP retailers, 2008 and 2017

Conversely, small retailers increased in each of these ten metro areas. In Atlanta, they increased from 57% to 72% of all retailers, while in Detroit, this increase was from 74% to 77%. In New York, the rate of small retailers almost doubled, moving from 29% to 48%.

dot_plot("Small retail")

Small retailers as a percentage of all SNAP retailers, 2008 and 2017

Lastly, for local foods storesprimarily farmers markets and food co-opsincreases in numbers were more modest compared to all SNAP retailers. Aside from Boston, local foods make up less than 2% of all SNAP retailers within this group. In Boston, however, the percentage increased from 2% to 5% during this time frame. In this way, these data might identify areas where local policies may be playing a key role at shaping food options for SNAP recipients.

dot_plot("Local foods")

Local foods as a percentage of all SNAP retailers, 2008 and 2017

Drilling down deeper into these data, the tables below show the highest and lowest percentages of local food retailers among MSAs with at least 250 retailers in 2017. The top group has several cities from Michigan and Massachusetts, while the bottom group features multiple cities from Texas and other states in the Southeast.

stores_msa_chg1<-stores %>%
  gather(Y2008:Y2017,key="year",value="present") %>%
  filter(present==1 & msa_fips>0) %>%
  group_by(msa_name,msa_short,store_group,year) %>%
  summarise(store_count=n()) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(msa_name,msa_short,year)%>%
  mutate(store_count_all=sum(store_count),
         store_pct=round(store_count/store_count_all*100,2)) %>%
  filter(year == "Y2017" & store_group=="Local foods" & store_count_all>250) %>% 
  arrange(-store_pct) %>%
  ungroup()

stores_msa_chg1_top20<-stores_msa_chg1[1:20,] %>%
  select(msa_name,store_count,store_count_all,store_pct) %>%
  rename("MSA"=msa_name,
         "Local food retailers"=store_count,
         "All SNAP retailers"=store_count_all,
         "Local food retail rate"=store_pct)

Potential research directions

On their own, these retailer data can provide insight into how retailer participation in SNAP varied in the years during and after the Great Recession. The initial summary given here indicates that patterns of participation varied by both store types and locations. Future research with these data could consider questions such as the following:

  • What local or regional policies might have shaped retailers decisions to become SNAP authorized? As in the Boston example above, how do local efforts result in differing patterns of retailer authorization.
  • How does the shifting geography of SNAP retailers in this period correlate with existing/emerging patterns of residential segregation?
  • Within urban areas, which neighborhoods saw the greatest increases in SNAP authorized retailers during this period? What drove these increases?
  • Why did some stores (Grocers and Specialty retailers) peak in number in 2012 while others continued to increase?
  • Did benefit redemptions increase in zip codes with a greater number of SNAP retailers, and did this vary by the types of new stores?
  • Who benefited financially from increased retailer authorizations? Who owned newly authorized stores?

Answering these and other questions will require additional work to identify policies and actors affecting enrollment at local, state, and regional scales. Yet, as the brief example of local foods outlets above shows, these data might help publicize initiatives that better support regional food systems and increase access to healthy foods.
